<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section class="seo-ed-faq">
  <div class="seo-ed-faq-inner">
    <div class="seo-ed-faq-intro">
      <span class="seo-ed-chapter-label">COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
      <h2>Retirement Income FAQ</h2>
      <p>Get answers to the most common questions about creating retirement income.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="seo-ed-btn-primary">Schedule Income Review</a>
    </div>
    <div class="seo-ed-faq-items">
      <div class="seo-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="seo-ed-faq-question">How much retirement income do I need? <span>+</span></button>
        <div class="seo-ed-faq-answer">Most retirees need 70-90% of their pre-retirement income, but this varies based on lifestyle, healthcare costs, travel plans, and whether your mortgage is paid off. We analyze your actual expenses and goals to determine your specific income need, then build a plan to meet it sustainably.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="seo-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="seo-ed-faq-question">What is the 4% rule? <span>+</span></button>
        <div class="seo-ed-faq-answer">The 4% rule suggests withdrawing 4% of your portfolio in year one, then adjusting for inflation annually. While it's a useful starting point, it's not perfect — it doesn't account for your specific situation, changing markets, or tax efficiency. We customize withdrawal rates based on your age, risk tolerance, income sources, and market conditions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="seo-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="seo-ed-faq-question">How do I create guaranteed retirement income? <span>+</span></button>
        <div class="seo-ed-faq-answer">Guaranteed income typically comes from Social Security, pensions, and annuities. Social Security provides a base (we optimize when you claim), pensions offer payments if you have one, and annuities can fill gaps if you need more guaranteed income. The key is building a guaranteed income floor that covers your essential expenses, then using investments for discretionary spending.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="seo-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="seo-ed-faq-question">Should I take Social Security early? <span>+</span></button>
        <div class="seo-ed-faq-answer">It depends on your health, other income sources, and need for cash flow. Claiming at 62 permanently reduces benefits by up to 30%, but makes sense if you need the income or have health concerns. Delaying to 70 increases benefits by 8% per year after full retirement age. We model your specific scenario to identify the optimal claiming strategy.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="seo-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="seo-ed-faq-question">What is sequence of returns risk? <span>+</span></button>
        <div class="seo-ed-faq-answer">Sequence of returns risk is the danger of experiencing market losses early in retirement when you're withdrawing money. If your portfolio drops 30% in year one and you're taking withdrawals, you're selling low and locking in losses — making it harder to recover. We mitigate this risk through bucket strategies, guaranteed income floors, dynamic withdrawal adjustments, and proper asset allocation.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

